ssacre are dealt with -- t17 Wherein my father retires after 43 years service with the Hudson’s Bay Company -- t18 Wherein he makes the acquaintance of several gamblers and desperadoes who haunted the traders’ camps along the Oregon Trail -- t19 In which he races horses with the desperadoes one of whom comes to a tragic end -- t20 In which he tells of his success in trading with the immigrants and of the massacre of one party by the Indians -- t21 In which he becomes the interpreter for Major Haller and accompanies a crude young lieutenant -- t22 In which he narrates some painful incidents in the Indian war -- t23 Wherein he ends his work with the soldiers and is obliged to leave the country -- t24 In which he joins his father and returns to trade with immigrants at Soda Springs -- t25 In which he tells of some pioneers, and of the Mormon Rising in 1857 -- t26 In which he entertains some Indians royally and decides to form a settlement at Deer Lodge -- t27 Wherein is related something of the discovery of gold in Montana and the opening of new markets for the settlement in Deer Lodge Valley -- t28 Wherein Captain Grant — “Handsome” Grant — dies without leaving his son even the proverbial shilling -- t29 In which he builds the first good house in Deer Lodge Valley and with his Quarra, enters on a new period of existence -- t30 In which he rewards the honesty of Little Dog for restoring his stolen horses -- t31 Wherein he makes a couple of trips among the Indians in search of stolen horses; Brown, a discouraged companion, shoots himself -- t32 Wherein he tells of his big freighting outfit and of the advent of “bad men” — white robbers and murderers — into Montana -- t33 In which the Vigilantes are seen to take the law in their own hands and the rascally sheriff is one of the first to be hanged -- t34 In which he lends his horse to the Vigilance Committee setting out from Hell’s Gate on their grim mission of death to law breakers -- t35 In which he tells of the decisive way in which the Vigilantes rid the country of highwaymen, three of them being hanged to the corners of Baron O’Keefe’s stable -- t36 Wherein he goes down to St. Louis by stage spending his money like water. He puts up at the Olive House and does business in a pleasant and leisurely way -- t37 In which he gives an insight into methods of doing business in St. Louis in the sixties when his purchases amounted to twenty-eight thousand dollars -- t38 Wherein he describes the tiresome stage journey from Omaha, where he had abandoned the still more tiresome Missouri boat. The stage upsets once and breaks the monotony. He kills his first buffalo -- t39 In which his milling venture did not satisfy his impatient nature, and he is tricked into disposing of it for three hundred gallons of homemade liquor -- t40 In which his new livery stable is burned, his pet saddle horse killed by a champagne bottle, and there is seen the beginning of the end of his days in Montana -- t41 In which Conrad Kohrs, afterward millionaire and Cattle King buys his ranch for $19,000 -- t42 Wherein he and Johnny Healy have a taste of adventure and he loses his sack of gold nuggets on his trip to St. Louis -- t43 He suddenly determines to go back to Three Rivers from St. Louis instead of going up to the Red River and his wild western guise startles his relatives -- t44 In which he renews old friendships and revisits old scenes, his memory sharpened with many regrets -- t45 He returns to the west, reaching the Red River by way of St. Louis and Fort Abercrombie -- t46 Red River — My arrival at Mr. McKay’s -- t47 He describes the conditions of life in the Red River Settlement — their work and amusements; their probity and fine harmony -- t48 He returns to Montana and his family, bringing a company of Red River Half-breeds with him to bring his freight train of carts and wagons back to the Red River -- t49 On his arrival at Deer Lodge he finds his Quarra is dead, his business shattered and his trusted clerk leaving the country with saddle-bags heavy with gold -- t50 His life is threatened by a jealous Mexican whose hand is stayed by memories of old kindness; then leaving about $50,000 worth of property behind him he sets out for the Red River -- t51 The Red River caravan has a most amiable but tiresome encounter with a band of Blackfeet who are intensely appreciative of past kindness. Grant and his seven year old son running buffalo -- t52 A band of Assiniboine Indians next meet the caravan, and a double guard is straightaway put upon the horses at night -- t53 In which he is kept busy watching the Cree guide obtained in the Assiniboine camp, and his suspicions of treachery are fulfilled -- t54 He makes a new home for himself along the Red River valley and marries Clotilde Bruneau, the daughter of a county judge who was the leader of the French population around St. Boniface -- t55 He makes a trip to the United States for relief wheat -- t56 Governor McDougall coming from Canada is turned back at the boundary by Riel’s men, and Riel marching back to Fort Garry takes peaceful possession of the old post -- t57 The arrival of Mr. D.A. Smith as commissioner and the general meeting at Fort Garry -- t58 He is nominated as delegate to the Provisional Government but Riel remembering his part during the rising refuses to recognize him as a delegate, and carrying his enmity further imprisons him -- t59 The Portage Uprising -- t60 In which he contracts to bring the Canadian Volunteers from the Red River to the Lake of the Woods. The trip is made with difficulty and Grant conceives a great contempt for the militiamen’s ability -- t61 First Election in Manitoba -- t62 Mr. D.A. Smith’s Election -- t63 My speculation in scrip -- t64 Change of Manitoba after the Transfer -- t65 Captain Moberley going west -- t66 Fever in my family -- t67 My first meeting with C. Allard partner of Mr. Pablo -- t68 The bad luck I had with giving my cattle [on] share -- t69 Property lost by fire -- t70 Bought a Saw Mill and Gristmill; Sailing on the railroad and selling land -- t71 My first trip to Montana -- t72 My return trip -- t73 My trip to BC and Alberta -- t74 Manitoba to Banff to Edmonton and back to Manitoba —1889 or 1890 -- t75 The move [to] Alberta, 1891 -- tNotes -- tAppendix 1 Genealogical Charts of the Grant Family, by Anita Steele -- tAppendix 2 Descriptive Genealogy of the Grant Family, by Anita Steele -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBorn in 1833 at Fort Edmonton, Johnny Grant lived through and recorded many historical events in the northwest, and died within sight of the same fort in 1907. Grant participated in the fur trade, was instrumental in the early stages of ranching in Montana, and played a pivotal role in the Riel Resistance of 1869-70. His life and career exemplifies that of many independent Metis traders, and his memoir offers a fascinating glimpse into the Metis experience on the northwestern frontier in the last half of the nineteenth century. With an introduction by Gerhard Ens, Johnny Grant's memoirs will be of interest to fur trade and Metis history enthusiasts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFrontier and pioneer lifezCanada, Western. 0aFrontier and pioneer lifezMontana. 0aMétisvBiography. 0aPioneerszCanada, WesternvBiography. 0aRancherszMontanavBiography. 0aRanchingzMontanaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh  aColonial Studies.  aIndigenous History.  aNorth American History.1 aEns, Gerhard J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBoo